<p>
Philips Hue is a light eco-system that include Light bulbs and lamps, a bridge, a remote, a portal and an app. The wireless light bulbs can change color, dim, flash and pulse. They are LED bulbs and eco-friendly and work with any standard light socket.
</p>

<h2 class="subtitle">
  <span class="sentence">The connection process is </span>complex
</h2>
<p>
The connection process is complex not particularly because it’s explained poorly but because the user has to understand the role of every player in the system. The bridge is at the heart of the Hue system. It is controlling all the settings of the lights and it is also used to enable the bulbs communication with each other and the portal via Internet. The user may start by screwing the light bulbs and turn the power on. Then, the Bridge has to connect to a power outlet. After that, the ethernet cable should be plugged between the bridge and an ethernet port on the Wi-Fi router. A blue light light up on the bridge. From there, the user should download the Philips Hue app. Once opened, the app automatically searches for Hue bridges. When the new Hue bridge is found, the user can tap the ‘set-up’ button that appears. Instructions appears on the next screen indicating that the user should push the link button on the Hue bridge. After the Philips Hue connects, the user will have to accept terms and conditions. For iOS users, Homekit and Siri can also be configured. Then all the lights bulbs can be added and organized into rooms.
</p>

